<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-687-703  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 687 703.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Dec 10 1990 v9 n26 p64(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Govt. loses 14 out of 164 ADP protests in 3 quarters of 1990. (USGeneral Services Administration Board of Contract Appeals protestreport)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Power, Kevin.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Services Administration. Board of ContractAppealsCourt CasesGovernment ContractsEquipment AcquisitionData AnalysisUnited States. Information Resources Management Service.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Most GSBCA protests don't stay the course. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Govt.andP;  Loses 147 Out of 164 ADP Protests in 3 Quarters of 1990andM;The government lost 14 of 164 ADP protests decided during the first threequarters of fiscal 1990, according to the General Services Administration'slatest protest report.andM;The GSA Board of Contract Appeals denied 26 protest and dismissed 14 cases.andO;A total of 110 cases either were settled or withdrawn, indicating that manyagencies and vendors resolve disputes after formal protests are filed.andM;The report, published by the Acquisition Evaluation and Analysis Branch inGSA's IRM Service, said the board processed the cases in an average of 20workdays and the results have been fairly consistent.andP;  The branch maintainsan automated database of all 1,032 GSBCA decisions issued since 1985.andM;More than half of the protests decided were filed against the militaryservices.andP;  The Army had the most protests with 27.andP;  The Navy was second with23, followed by the Air Force with 15 and the Defense Department with 11.andM;Protesters prevailed in six of the 76 cases.andP;  The board granted one Air Forceprotest, two DOD protests and three Navy protests.andP;  It granted no protestsagainsts the Army.andM;As for the 88 civilian agency protests, the departments of Commerce,Interior, Transportation, Treasury and Veterans Affairs together had eightcases decided.andP;  No agency lost more than two cases.andM;Since 1985, the board has granted 127 protests and denied 148.andP;  The boarddismissed 123 cases: 260 cases were withdrawn; 374 cases were settled.andO;</TEXT></DOC>